{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"162e8072-45c9-4787-aed5-0813d092d676","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncDisposable\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via the constructor\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization — runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup work (e.g., seed a database, start a service)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup\n    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async teardown\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points (MSTest 3.x):**\n\n- **`TestContext` injection** — pass it via the constructor; no more `[TestInitialize]` property-setter tricks.\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize] async Task` (runs per-test). For class-level async setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` on a static method.\n- **Cleanup** — implement `IAsyncDisposable` (or `IDisposable` for sync) instead of `[TestCleanup]` if you prefer the dispose pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"03f160bd-e375-4173-8afe-1f44837c7493","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"0C04:185A87:41381B:4BC3B3:69F00E16"},"id":"d5050ac1-d761-474d-a976-bd697aecf9e5","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:32:15.762Z","parentId":"4b26fafb-9adf-4ea7-888e-b6cd561f9837"}
